00:06:02.799 --> 00:06:09.519
Why don't we? Yeah, so when the Affordable Care Act was put into place in about 2015,

00:06:10.079 --> 00:06:15.519
one of the things that was mandated there is insurance companies can no longer deny people

00:06:15.519 --> 00:06:20.480
coverage for pre-existing conditions. So it doesn't matter what conditions you have. You

00:06:20.480 --> 00:06:25.279
have to get insurance. You can't discriminate based on rates for those conditions that someone

00:06:25.279 --> 00:06:30.559
has. So one of the things that is in place in order to ensure that that happens is what's

00:06:30.559 --> 00:06:36.320
called risk adjustment. And so throughout the year, all health insurance companies submit their

00:06:36.320 --> 00:06:42.559
claims data and their diagnosis data for their entire populations to these government-maintained

00:06:42.559 --> 00:06:49.839
servers. And then you get credit for the risk. So members have certain conditions that counts them

00:06:49.839 --> 00:06:53.760
as risky or not risky. There's a bunch of interaction factors and a whole lot of math

00:06:53.760 --> 00:07:00.640
involved in calculating how much risk a member has. And so then at the end of the year is when

00:07:00.640 --> 00:07:06.239
the risk adjustment takes place. So insurers who insure a riskier population actually get

00:07:06.880 --> 00:07:12.480
transfer dollars from the insurers who insure a less risky population. So it's entirely budget

00:07:12.480 --> 00:07:19.760
neutral. There's no government money involved in changing hands. They facilitate that transfer

00:07:19.760 --> 00:07:27.040
between those insurers but not anything else. So if one insurer insures a bunch of like elderly

00:07:27.040 --> 00:07:32.720
people with multiple comorbidities and one insurer insures a bunch of healthy college students, the

00:07:32.720 --> 00:07:36.720
one who insures a bunch of healthy college students is going to owe money to that other insurer at the

00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:43.359
end of the year. Just to say like we're covering more risk than you are. And then there's the

00:07:43.359 --> 00:07:50.320
process. So I have a sister team who's involved in the risk adjustment and I am in charge of the

00:07:50.320 --> 00:07:54.720
audit of the risk adjustment. So once you've submitted all of this data, the government

00:07:54.720 --> 00:07:58.799
takes a representative sample of your population and comes back to you and say prove it. Prove that

00:07:58.799 --> 00:08:03.920
these members have the conditions that you say that they have. So we have to go and collect

00:08:03.920 --> 00:08:08.880
medical records, talk to doctors, code all of those records, and then recalculate the risk and prove

00:08:08.959 --> 00:08:13.920
that the population distribution is as risky as we said it was throughout the year.

